	<h1 class="page-title">Valve Hardware Beta EULA Confirms Controller</h1>

	<div class="meta">By Brian P Rubin | 26 September 2013 | <a href="http://www.insidegamingdaily.com/2013/09/26/valve-hardware-beta-eula-confirms-controller/#comments" class="comments-link"  title="Comment on Valve Hardware Beta EULA Confirms Controller">3 Comments</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>
	
	<p style="text-align: center;"><a title="steam controller by Machinima_com, on Flickr" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/44399775@N06/9952521074/"><img alt="steam controller" src="http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3792/9952521074_cb7e841fb8.jpg" width="500" height="227" /></a></p>
<p>As you probably saw yesterday, Valve made an announcement regarding its latest innovation—namely, that of <a href="http://www.insidegamingdaily.com/2013/09/25/valve-announces-steam-machines-a-living-room-box-for-pc-gaming/">Steam Machines</a> (what, Steam Box isn’t fancy-sounding enough, Gabe?). While there were plenty of hints dropped that the third and final living room announcement would concern the company’s controller, the EULA to participate in the <a href="https://store.steampowered.com/hardwarebeta/">Steam Machine hardware beta</a> puts any questions of such an announcement to rest.</p>
<p>From the agreement, emphasis ours:</p>
<blockquote><p>“Valve Corporation (‘Valve’, ‘We’, ‘Us’ or ‘Our’) has developed and produced prototypes of entertainment system hardware and software, including a set-top box running custom software <b>and a game controller</b> (collectively: ‘Beta Products’). These Beta Products are currently being prepared for a limited beta testing program (‘Beta Program’) involving select end users of Our online service known as Steam (‘Steam’).”</p></blockquote>
<p>BOOM. Sure, we knew that the controller was next, but now there’s no doubt.</p>
<p>So that leaves some other questions—namely, what form will that controller take? I have my doubts that we’ll actually find much out when Valve makes its last announcement tomorrow. Despite the fact that we’ve now gone through two announcements for SteamOS and Steam Machines, we have yet to actually see either thing in action, samples, details, examples…I predict lots more vague language and weird cardboard-cutout styled images that people interpret as proof that <i>Half-Life 3</i> is coming soon.</p>
<p>Even still, there’s been lots of talk that Valve is looking to incorporate biometric data into its input device. I doubt that it’ll bother with a touch screen or something, but maybe some method of measuring your pulse or your clammy hands. What do you think the Steam Machine controller will be like? What do you think Valve’s slapped on there? And, by that same token, what do you think the company has <i>omitted</i>? Lots of buttons, sure. But maybe fewer than the Xbox 360 pad? Let us know what you think.</p>
<p>[<a href="https://store.steampowered.com/hardwarebeta/">Valve</a>]</p>
<p><span class='st_facebook_hcount' st_title='Valve Hardware Beta EULA Confirms Controller' st_url='http://www.insidegamingdaily.com/2013/09/26/valve-hardware-beta-eula-confirms-controller/'></span><span st_via='InsideGaming' st_username='InsideGaming' class='st_twitter_hcount' st_title='Valve Hardware Beta EULA Confirms Controller' st_url='http://www.insidegamingdaily.com/2013/09/26/valve-hardware-beta-eula-confirms-controller/'></span><span class='st_plusone_hcount' st_title='Valve Hardware Beta EULA Confirms Controller' st_url='http://www.insidegamingdaily.com/2013/09/26/valve-hardware-beta-eula-confirms-controller/'></span></p>	
		
